etymologies: early 19th century. Either from classical Latin renuntiātor reporter or informer (2nd century a.d.), in post-classical Latin also renouncer (late 2nd or early 3rd century in Tertullian; from renuntiāt-, past participial stem of renuntiāre + -or), or from renunciate + -or. Compare Italian rinunziatore

definitions: A person who renounces something; a renunciant.
